        "description": "Standard for 1064 nm cleaning to achieve uniform energy delivery; 50 kHz recommended for SiC to balance speed and limit heat accumulation (trade-off: higher rates increase throughput but risk thermal stress). Source: Academic literature in Optics Express (2017) on repetition rate effects in ceramic laser processing."
      },
      "pulseWidth": {
        "min": 0.1,
        "max": 1000,
        "value": 20,
        "unit": "ns",
        "description": "Nanosecond regime preferred for cost-effective cleaning of SiC; 20 ns minimizes heat-affected zone (HAZ <10 μm) due to SiC's high melting point (~2700°C) and reflectivity (~40% at 1064 nm). Picosecond (ps) for ultra-precision but less common industrially. Source: Laser physics research in Applied Surface Science (2019) on pulsed laser ablation of SiC."
      },
      "scanSpeed": {
        "min": 10,
        "max": 5000,
        "unit": "mm/s",
        "value": 2000,
        "description": "Effective range for contaminant removal without excessive heat buildup; 2000 mm/s recommended for light oils/greases on SiC, slower (500-1000 mm/s) for heavy rust. Higher speeds for large areas. Source: Industry standards from Laserax cleaning systems manuals and Journal of Cleaner Production (2020) case study on ceramics."
      },
      "passCount": {
        "min": 1,
        "max": 10,
        "value": 2,
        "unit": "passes",
        "description": "Typically 1-3 passes for complete removal of light contaminants on SiC; multi-pass (2 recommended) for layered/heavy buildup to avoid single-pass overload and damage. Single pass viable for thin films. Source: Industry practice in Laser Cleaning Handbook (2022) and case studies on ceramic substrates in Materials Science and Engineering: A (2016)."
      },
      "overlapRatio": {
        "min": 10,
        "max": 90,
        "value": 60,
        "unit": "%",
        "description": "Ensures uniform coverage without gaps or over-ablation; 60% recommended for SiC to optimize energy distribution and minimize uneven heating given its thermal properties. Higher (70-80%) for heavy contamination. Source: Process optimization studies in International Journal of Advanced Manufacturing Technology (2019) on scan strategies for laser cleaning."
